<!DOCTYPE sub.page	SYSTEM "../Symbols.dtd">
<sub.page xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
	xmlns="http://webmath.math.ualberta.ca/v1/Book"
	xsi:schemaLocation="http://webmath.math.ualberta.ca/v1/Book    http://webmath.math.ualberta.ca/Schemas/v1/Book.xsd"
	id="UpperTriangularMatrices">
	<title>Illustration of Upper Triangular Matrices</title>
	<sub.page.body>
		<block>
			<para>Every <latex>(1,1)</latex>-identity matrix is an upper triangular matrix.</para>
			
			
			<para>An example of an upper triangular <latex>(2,2)</latex> matrix is</para>
			<math.display>
				<latex>
					<![CDATA[
					\begin{bmatrix}
					2 & 1 \\
					0 & 3
					\end{bmatrix}
					]]>
				</latex>
			</math.display>
			
			
			<para>An example of an upper triangular <latex>(3,3)</latex> matrix is</para>
			<math.display>
				<latex>
					<![CDATA[
					\begin{bmatrix}
					7 & 0 & 3 \\
					0 & 1 & 3 \\
					0 & 0 & 2
					\end{bmatrix}
					]]>
				</latex>
			</math.display>
			
			
			<para>An example of an upper triangular <latex>(4,4)</latex> matrix is</para>
			<math.display>
				<latex>
					<![CDATA[
					\begin{bmatrix}
					9 & 3 & 2 & 6  \\
					0 & 7 & 4 & 3  \\
					0 & 0 & 0 & 1\\
					0 & 0 & 0 & 4
					\end{bmatrix}
					]]>
				</latex>
			</math.display>
		</block>
		
		<block>
			<para>Other examples of upper triangular matrices include</para>
			
			<ul>
				<li><para>all diagonal matrices and,</para></li>
				<li><para>in  particular, all identity matrices</para></li>
			</ul>
		</block>
	</sub.page.body>
</sub.page>